Package org.apache.logging.log4j.plugins.di

Class Key<T>

java.lang.Object
org.apache.logging.log4j.plugins.di.Key<T>
Type Parameters:
T - type of key
All Implemented Interfaces:
Comparable<Key<T>>, org.apache.logging.log4j.util.StringBuilderFormattable
public class Key<T> extends Object implements org.apache.logging.log4j.util.StringBuilderFormattable, Comparable<Key<T>>
Keys represent a reified type with an optional QualifierType type, name, and namespace. A key is used in two related contexts: describing an InjectionPoint requesting a dependency for injection and describing a binding where a scoped factory is registered for providing dependencies.

  • Constructor Details

    • Key

      protected Key()
      Anonymous subclasses override this constructor to instantiate this Key based on the type given. For example, to represent the equivalent of an annotated field @Named("abc") Map<String, List<String>> field, this constructor would be used like so: 
      
 Key<Map<String, List<String>>> key = new @Named("abc") Key<>() {};
 // or equivalently
 var key = new @Named("abc") Key<Map<String, List<String>>>() {};

      public final String getNamespace()
      Returns the namespace of this key. If this key has no defined namespace, then this returns an empty string.

      API note: a namespace of the empty string is considered the default namespace which is used when no namespace is defined or if the namespace is explicitly defined as the empty string.

    • getOrder

      public final OptionalInt getOrder()
      Returns the ordinal value of this key. Keys that are otherwise equal can be compared by this ordinal using the natural integer comparator where ties should default to keeping an existing binding intact.

    • getSuppliedType

      public final <P> @Nullable Key<P> getSuppliedType()
      If this key's type T is a subtype of Supplier<P> for some supplied type P, then this returns a new key with that type argument along with the same name and qualifier type as this key.
      Returns:
      a new instance from this using the supplied type or null if this key did not contain a supplier type

    • getParameterizedTypeArgument

      public final <P> @Nullable Key<P> getParameterizedTypeArgument(int arg)
      If this key's type T is a parameterized type such that T can be represented as R<P0, P1, P2, ...> with raw type R and type arguments P0, P1, etc., then this returns a new key corresponding to the requested parameterized type argument along with the same remaining values as this key.
      Parameters:
      arg - the index of the type argument to create a new key from
      Returns:
      a new instance from this using the type argument if defined or null
      Throws:
      IndexOutOfBoundsException - if arg is negative or otherwise outside the bounds of the actual number of type arguments of this key's type
